name: 04-Model-Training-and-Prediction
content:
Objective

The objective of this section is to provide a comprehensive overview of how to train, evaluate, and deploy a Random Forest model to predict the final quality of manufactured items. The model integrates multiple data sources, including human error, raw material degradation, sensor performance, and demand data, to ensure accurate and reliable quality predictions.


Overview of Random Forest Model

  • Random Forest is an ensemble learning technique that builds multiple Decision Trees during training.
  • Each tree produces a prediction, and the final outcome is determined by:
  • Majority voting → for classification tasks (e.g., good vs. defective quality).
  • Averaging → for regression tasks (e.g., continuous quality score).
  • Benefits of Random Forest:
  • Reduces overfitting compared to individual decision trees.
  • Handles high-dimensional and heterogeneous data effectively.
  • Provides insights into feature importance, highlighting the most critical quality drivers.

Model Training

  1. Data Preparation
  • Merge human error, raw material, sensor, and demand datasets into a unified feature matrix.
  • Split the dataset into training (70–80%) and testing (20–30%) subsets.
  • Normalize or encode categorical variables where required.

2.Training Process

  • Construct multiple decision trees, each trained on a bootstrap sample (random subset of rows and features).
  • Aggregate predictions across all trees to generate the final output.

3.Hyperparameter Tuning

1. Optimize model performance by adjusting:

  • n_estimators → Number of trees in the forest.
  • max_depth → Maximum depth of each tree to control complexity.
  • max_features → Number of features considered at each split.
  • min_samples_split / min_samples_leaf → Minimum data points required for splits and leaf nodes.
  • class_weight → Adjust for class imbalance if defective products are rare.

2.Model Evaluation

  • For classification tasks (predicting defect vs. non-defect):
  • Metrics: Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1-score, ROC-AUC.
  • For regression tasks (predicting continuous quality scores):
  • Metrics: Mean Absolute Error (MAE), Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE), R² Score.
